tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMusic education in Canada is a vast enterprise that encompasses teaching and learning in thousands of public and private schools, community groups, and colleges and universities. It involves participants from infancy to the elderly in formal and informal settings. Nevertheless, as post-secondary faculties of music and programs are growing significantly, academic books and materials grounded in a Canadian perspective are scarce. This book attempts to fill that need by offering a collection of essays that look critically at various global issues in music education from a Canadian perspective. Topics range from a discussion of the roots of music education in Canada and analysis of music education practices across the country to perspectives on popular music, distance education, technology, gender, globalization, Indigenous traditions, and community music in music education. Foreword by composer R. Murray Schafer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxInstruction and studyxCanada. 0aMusicxInstruction and studyzCanada. 0aMusiquexÉtude et enseignementxCanadaxCanada. 4aEducation. 4aMusic. 7aEDUCATION / Aims & Objectives.2bisacsh1 aBeynon, Carol A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeynon, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolden, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Wayne D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCountryman, June, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula